From Kyiv to Palm Beach

Thus ends Routh=E2=80=99s ego trip to Ukraine, which, he admits, was an abj=
ect failure=E2=80=94as was he, personally. =E2=80=9CI am the failure, the h=
ypocrite, the loser that wants the world to change but let communism beat m=
e down and exhaust me and send me home,=E2=80=9D he writes. =E2=80=9CI pers=
onally have failed humanity and wasted 5 months with no measurable success.=
=E2=80=9D No less humbly, he adds: =E2=80=9CIn the war between myself and U=
kraine, where I had hoped that I could bend Ukraine towards democracy and f=
reedom and human rights and be a representative of the USA, I lost the figh=
t. It was a childish idealistic endeavor that was unwinnable.=E2=80=9D

But it is not just his fault, he concludes. It is also Ukraine=E2=80=99s, w=
hich is why he returns home with such bitterness and resentment of the plac=
e. On one hand, he acknowledges that Ukraine is fighting on the side of goo=
d for the
sake of the entire world, but he also feels that Ukrainian society is deepl=
y cynical and still Communist. Ukrainians, Routh gripes, always wanted to k=
now =E2=80=9CWho is paying you?=E2=80=9D Given the spy games afoot there, i=
t is not an unreasonable question. But in it, Routh discovers Eastern Europ=
ean distrust of strangers and their motives=E2=80=94and is horrified by it.=
 =E2=80=9CWhat type of childhood must that be like growing up where everyth=
ing has a price?=E2=80=9D he wonders. =E2=80=9CIs the simple act of love an=
d caring omitted from day to day life as there is no mechanism for reimburs=
ement?=E2=80=9D At the same time, he is angered by Ukrainians=E2=80=99 =E2=
=80=9Clack of appreciation for those that pay to travel to Ukraine and risk=
 death to fight for their freedom.=E2=80=9D Foreigners, he writes, =E2=80=
=9Cexpend great sums of money=E2=80=9D but aren=E2=80=99t feted as heroes. =
The irony of his complaint about Ukrainians=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Ctransactional=
=E2=80=9D nature is lost on him entirely.

Ukraine, he feels, is unable but also unwilling to win
the war, in part because the conflict is an excuse to milk the West for cas=
h. At the same time, he blames the West for not giving Ukraine enough resou=
rces to win, and says the U.S. is not doing enough to counter the threats f=
rom the dictatorships of the world. =E2=80=9CWe should encircle Taiwan with=
 military ships=E2=80=9D lest the U.S. be seen as serving Taiwan up to Beij=
ing =E2=80=9Con a silver platter,=E2=80=9D he writes. The solution to every=
 problem is American power, Routh declares=E2=80=94=E2=80=9CWe should be th=
e peacekeepers and the policemen for the world=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94while simul=
taneously condemning American defense spending as a waste of resources and =
=E2=80=9Cstupid.=E2=80=9D

The far right might seize on what they perceive as Routh=E2=80=99s passiona=
te Ukraine advocacy, using it either to paint Routh as a Democrat or to fur=
ther drive their base=E2=80=99s animosity toward Kyiv. But to read Routh=E2=
=80=99s book is to see a very different picture of him than the one painted=
 in the media. It is tempting to call his foreign policy
views confused=E2=80=94which they are=E2=80=94but the far more relevant con=
clusion is that he is mentally ill. Despite his overconfidence and self-agg=
randizement, he is clearly unable to understand the world around him. He fi=
nds it baffling, infuriating, and, well, incoherent.

That=E2=80=99s all for me this week, friends. I=E2=80=99ll catch you back h=
ere next week. Until then, good night. Tomorrow will be worse.

Julia

